10:05.320 --> 10:07.062
You're not growing when you're in your comfort zone.

10:07.763 --> 10:17.157
If I wouldn't have taken this decision around three more than three years ago, I wouldn't be with you in the same podcast track here at Vibhan in Saudi Arabia and Riyadh.

10:17.898 --> 10:19.941
I'm glad you took that decision.

10:19.961 --> 10:20.421
I'm glad.

10:22.284 --> 10:23.646
I want to ask you a question.

10:25.068 --> 10:26.610
You are very, very

10:27.682 --> 10:55.922
multicultural and I love that you said that you're an arabist and I love that you so when we were speaking of your name I wanted to make sure how to pronounce it you told me it's Swiss actually and you've worked in London California Boston Madrid Spain you're here telling me more about how can one actually grow when he's surrounded by different cultures and people and not only one how can an entrepreneur

10:56.546 --> 10:58.188
grow when he's multi-cultured?

10:59.589 --> 11:07.018
Well, I think actually it's an asset to be multi-cultured because every culture has pluses and minuses.

11:08.199 --> 11:10.222
And we can learn from cultures.

11:10.622 --> 11:16.108
So I'm American but I've learned so much from, I live in Spain, from the Spanish culture.

11:16.148 --> 11:19.412
I've learned from the Middle Eastern culture.

11:19.432 --> 11:24.498
And so when you're multi-cultured, usually

11:24.802 --> 11:26.845
you have a lot of emotional intelligence.

11:28.007 --> 11:36.659
And today emotional intelligence is probably one of the most important factors in your ability to grow, even within a company.

11:37.080 --> 11:39.543
When you're an entrepreneur, you need emotional intelligence.

11:40.545 --> 11:46.534
And so what I like to tell my students is that they need to be able to master rhetoric.

11:46.694 --> 11:49.518
I don't know if you know what rhetoric means, but it's a Greek term.

11:50.239 --> 11:51.340
Rhetoric has three parts.

11:51.421 --> 11:52.402
It's logos,

11:52.578 --> 11:54.160
Ethos and pathos.

11:54.361 --> 11:57.245
Very good.

11:57.405 --> 12:00.309
So logos is the arguments that we make.

12:01.230 --> 12:05.056
Like you say that, I'll give you an example.

12:05.276 --> 12:15.811
When Steve Jobs introduced the iPhone, he could have said, this is a device that allows you to search the web, take pictures and make calls.

12:16.632 --> 12:20.818
Pure logos, arguments, engineering arguments.

12:21.442 --> 12:23.244
Ethos is your credibility.

12:23.324 --> 12:24.245
He was very credible.

12:24.265 --> 12:26.047
He was president of Apple.

12:26.928 --> 12:30.732
But pathos is the emotions that you stir in the people.

12:31.373 --> 12:39.982
And so he didn't get up there in 2009 at that famous beach and say, this is a device that can take pictures, search the web and make calls.

12:40.603 --> 12:43.026
He got up there and he said, do you see this device?

12:43.867 --> 12:45.088
It's going to change your life.

12:46.490 --> 12:47.611
That is pure pathos.

12:48.592 --> 12:50.514
And we need to dream.

12:50.658 --> 12:53.522
We need to dream in our lives.

12:53.642 --> 12:56.386
My father always said to me, the day that you don't have a dream, you die.

12:57.628 --> 13:00.993
And now we're living in a world that is being disrupted by AI.

13:02.775 --> 13:04.738
And many of my students are very worried.

13:05.439 --> 13:07.663
How can I be future proof?

13:08.103 --> 13:18.418
Well, let me tell you, AI will never take over the human spirit of rhetoric, the ability to persuade others to inspire

13:18.914 --> 13:24.823
to have people have faith in you, leaders, leadership, all those things will never be replaced by AI.

13:25.484 --> 13:33.417
And so today when I see my students making presentations, they make incredible print, credible slides, data, all that, it's all done by AI.

13:34.158 --> 13:38.986
But when they have to stand in front of the audience, they're alone there.

13:39.006 --> 13:44.375
And that's when you're in front of humanity and you need to show what you're made of.

13:44.955 --> 13:46.578
And that will never be replaced by AI.

13:47.746 --> 13:55.594
That's very reassuring because we were having this very quick chat with your colleague now, right, before we start.

13:56.395 --> 13:57.877
And she's a master of AI.

13:57.897 --> 14:02.322
And I'm very afraid of she's a geek.

14:02.582 --> 14:03.263
That's amazing.

14:03.463 --> 14:04.184
We have a company.

14:04.204 --> 14:09.449
It's called Geek Peak is for like virtual stuff with CG and AI integrated.

14:09.549 --> 14:11.031
I should introduce her to the team.

14:12.192 --> 14:14.034
But AI.

14:14.882 --> 14:22.493
So actually, you're the second person that I interview in Beban, and they mention the term emotional intelligence.

14:22.513 --> 14:26.318
You know that I haven't heard it for more than a year and a half.

14:26.819 --> 14:26.959
Really?

14:26.979 --> 14:27.500
I haven't.

14:27.800 --> 14:29.523
No one is speaking about EQ.

14:29.703 --> 14:30.344
No one.

14:30.784 --> 14:31.606
It's so important.

14:31.806 --> 14:32.106
Yes.

14:32.407 --> 14:35.050
Because all we're speaking of now is AI.

14:35.070 --> 14:39.356
And I don't mind it if, as you said, if it's controlled, if I know how to use it.

14:40.638 --> 14:43.282
But speaking of

14:43.810 --> 14:58.053
Speaking of AI, how much are you supporting new projects or entrepreneurs that are actually infusing AI in their schemes or in their industries?

14:58.855 --> 15:00.818
Tremendously, we need to leverage AI.

15:01.800 --> 15:10.514
AI is here to stay, and it is a tremendous asset that we have in order to be more productive

15:10.850 --> 15:13.575
find cures to diseases, all kinds of things.

15:14.296 --> 15:15.919
But the problem is not AI.

15:16.159 --> 15:17.982
The problem is how we use AI.

15:18.984 --> 15:24.634
And what we're finding is that about 60% of the class is getting dumber and lazier using AI.

15:25.295 --> 15:27.338
The other 40% are really taking off.

15:28.019 --> 15:32.066
So, you know, and this term is called cognitive offloading.

15:32.247 --> 15:34.971
I have a TEDx talk in my LinkedIn that you can see on that.

15:35.612 --> 15:36.594
But essentially,

15:36.802 --> 15:46.495
we're trying to create a sense of urgency because if 60% of the class in universities and we've seen it here in Saudi Arabia, we've seen it in the US and Europe, it's a reality.

15:46.515 --> 15:49.439
60% of the class is getting dumber and lazier.

15:50.220 --> 15:53.244
If you don't use your brain, you lose it.

15:53.965 --> 15:55.147
It's like a must.

15:55.627 --> 16:00.574
And so we need to teach young people to do critical thinking.

16:00.594 --> 16:03.658
You went to school before AI.

16:04.279 --> 16:05.741
So you had to do critical thinking.

16:05.861 --> 16:06.482
So did I.

16:06.946 --> 16:11.512
But today, if you're a young person in school, you don't need to do critical thinking.

16:11.573 --> 16:12.995
You can let AI do it for you.

16:13.555 --> 16:19.444
And so you've never learned to use your brain, which is amazing.

16:19.764 --> 16:20.245
Exactly.

16:20.325 --> 16:24.391
So this is like a drug if you don't control it.

16:24.972 --> 16:27.716
And so we're here trying to create a sense of urgency.

16:27.756 --> 16:29.458
We're talking to a lot of different people.

16:29.570 --> 16:35.177
We're trying to create a movement around the right use of AI, the ethical use of AI.

16:35.738 --> 16:39.743
Because otherwise, we run the risk of losing generations of people.

16:41.305 --> 16:42.086
I totally agree.

16:42.246 --> 16:52.358
And it's hitting me to the core because once like, you know, when tragedy started to become part of our lives, yes, we kind of used it in the beginning.

16:53.420 --> 16:58.386
But I felt that the time I'm spending on finishing a task,

16:58.722 --> 17:05.309
If I was working on a task that takes five days, I can now finish it in less than a day.

17:06.470 --> 17:11.715
But yes, I'm honest, I felt so very lazy.

17:11.856 --> 17:13.057
I felt so very dumb.

17:13.197 --> 17:14.198
The imposter syndrome.

17:14.458 --> 17:14.819
Yeah.

17:15.179 --> 17:16.941
